abstract: UTICA, N.Y., Juno 30. -- Lackawanna train No. 6, leaving this city at 11:10 o'clock this morning, was wrecked near the station at Chadwick's, seven miles south of this city. abstract: LONDON, June 16. -- I don't suppose there is a phase more often employed in London just now than the magic one, "the height of the season." Society comes in from its country seat and uses it; the shopkeepers charge harrowing sums because of it. abstract: That pessimistic philosopher Schopenhauer made it a practice to read to his cook everything he wrote. abstract: AN order of the day issued by the German Kaiser completely revolutionizes Prussian infantry tradition by introducing a set of regulations making the individual soldier and not the company the unit of evolution. The new regulations will supersede those established by Emperor Frederick in 1888 -- which, by the way, were used by the Russians in the Far East -- and embody the experiences derived from the South-African war and the Russo-Japanese conflict.

abstract: WASHINGTON, July 10. -- According to a report issued by the Census Bureau to-day there were 163,176 persona in almshouses in the United States in 1904, and of these 111,817 were males. In 1880 the ratio of the almshouse paupers to the population was 132 to every 100,000 people.

abstract: PITTSBURG, July 14. -- The Rev. Father Tuzek, rector of St. Nicholas's Croatian Church at Millvale, has asked the authorities for twenty-five policemen to protect him while he holds services in the church to-morrow. Tuesday night the tourists will stop at the Hotel Champlain, on Lake Champlain, and Wednesday night will find them in the Canadian city.

abstract: ALBUQUERQUE, New Mexico, July 19. -- Senor Baca of Socorro, until recently District Attorney, is here with his family. abstract: Wall Street is trying to feel bullish. Prices have stopped declining, bullish information is extremely accessible, mysterious liquidation apparently has ceased, and the market has a "sold-out look." abstract: SPRING LAKE, N.J., July 21. -- On Monday, Aug. 6, the annual tennis tournament on the courts of the Spring Lake Casino will begin, and it is expected that a large number of out-of-town devotees of the game will compete. abstract: THE traveler who visited the Isthmus several years ago begins to observe changes on the way down. abstract: PITTSBURG, July 21. -- The Pittsburgs won to-day's game from the New Yorks, 8 to 2, and incidentally pushed the world's champions out of second place and took that position themselves. abstract: Three automobiles had narrow escapes from being submerged by the incoming tide at Long Beach yesterday afternoon. Their owners had driven down from the city, attracted by the announcement of a novel series of races on the beach. A severe storm drove every one to shelter about noon, and the salvage of motor cars, strung out at various points along the shore, constituted all the sport that was had for the rest of the day.

abstract: Wall Street is prone at times to take an extremely selfish view of prosperity. The speculator says, in effect: "Of what use is all this prosperity which we hear about incessantly if prices decline on it?" abstract: Speyer  Co., together with the Deutsche Bank of Berlin, are about to establish a new bank in the City of Mexico. abstract: SEA GIRT, N.J., July 25. -- The National Guardsmen from Paterson enjoyed fair weather to-day, after having experienced three rainy days and an extremely cold night last night. abstract: The transactions on the Stock Exchange yesterday, for the first time since July 2, reached 1,000,000 shares. abstract: ST. PETERSBURG, July 28. -- The switchboard of the Central Telegraph Station in St. Petersburg was burned out this morning, destroying all communication with the provinces. abstract: FISHKILL LANDING, N.Y., July 28. -- Charles Sondermeyer, foreman of the barber's shop in the Metropolitan Life Insurance Building, New York, and his bride, Theresa de Groote, just from Rotterdam, Holland, are spending their honeymoon at Fishkill Landing. abstract: Over fifty professional golfers have entered for the two-day tournament to be held on the public course at Van Cortlandt Park, beginning to-morrow and continuing through Wednesday. Over $400 in purses will be divided. The match will be 72 holes, medal play, 36 holes to be played each day. The prospect of fine scoring is bright, for practically all of the best local professional golfers are entered, including the open champion, Aleck Smith of Nassau.

abstract: ST. PETERSBURG, July 29. -- A party of men armed with revolvers forced their way yesterday into the Boussel printing establishment here. They made the foreman a prisoner and prevented the compositors from leaving the building. They then had printed 150,000 copies of the Viborg manifesto of the outlawed lower house of Parliament. Strangers calling at the establishment while this work was being done were detained to prevent their giving the alarm.

abstract: SHENECTADY, N.Y., July 30. -- After amusing circus audiences for thirty years with his jokes and antics, James G.
